WEBVTT

00:00:07.040 --> 00:00:07.350
Hi.

00:00:07.350 --> 00:00:08.940
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:08.940 --> 00:00:13.060
In lecture introduced the idea
of differentials and learned

00:00:13.060 --> 00:00:13.990
how to compute them.

00:00:13.990 --> 00:00:16.530
So I have a couple examples
here for you to do.

00:00:16.530 --> 00:00:22.780
So compute the differential d
of 7u to the ninth plus 34

00:00:22.780 --> 00:00:25.050
minus 5u to the minus third.

00:00:25.050 --> 00:00:28.480
And d of sine theta,
cosine theta.

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:31.230
So why don't you take a minute,
work those out and

00:00:31.230 --> 00:00:33.070
we'll come back and we'll
work them out together.

00:00:41.150 --> 00:00:42.290
All right, welcome back.

00:00:42.290 --> 00:00:44.200
So hopefully you had some
luck with these.

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:46.130
Let's go through them.

00:00:46.130 --> 00:00:50.910
So right, so a differential is
really, it's just another

00:00:50.910 --> 00:00:53.310
notation for something you
already know how to do.

00:00:53.310 --> 00:00:56.100
So it's another way of keeping
track of a derivative.

00:00:56.100 --> 00:01:00.750
The thing we don't write is we
don't write the over the d,

00:01:00.750 --> 00:01:02.220
the variable we're
differentiating

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:03.620
with respect to.

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:06.680
So we pick that up from
what we're taking the

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:07.550
differential of.

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:10.700
So in this case, we look
at this expression.

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:15.560
Let's do the first one first.
So we look at d 7u to the

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:18.970
ninth plus 34 minus 5u
to the minus third.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:22.070
And we just can distribute that
d through in the same way

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:25.080
that we can with ordinary
derivatives.

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:38.670
So OK, so this is equal to 7d of
u to the ninth plus d of 34

00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:43.910
minus 5d u to the minus third.

00:01:43.910 --> 00:01:45.870
And now we just do
the chain rule.

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:51.660
So here d of u to the ninth
is 9u to the eighth du.

00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:54.840
So that du comes out of that
chain rule that we're doing.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:58.720
So this is equal to-- so well,
7 and we drop the 9 down-- so

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:05.380
that's 63 u to the
eighth du plus--

00:02:05.380 --> 00:02:07.930
well OK, d of 34, 34
is a constant.

00:02:07.930 --> 00:02:08.630
It just kills it.

00:02:08.630 --> 00:02:10.200
That's 0.

00:02:10.200 --> 00:02:15.530
Minus 5d of u to the
minus third.

00:02:15.530 --> 00:02:18.070
So again, u to the
minus third.

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:19.750
That's just the power of u.

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:21.450
We apply our usual
rule for it.

00:02:21.450 --> 00:02:25.840
So it's minus 3u to
the minus 4du.

00:02:25.840 --> 00:02:28.240
du from the chain rule.

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:32.500
Again, and so we have minus 5
times minus 3 is plus 15.

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:34.570
Good, so I get to keep
my plus sign.

00:02:34.570 --> 00:02:36.430
Plus 15.

00:02:36.430 --> 00:02:38.140
What did I say? u to
the minus 4du.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:42.980
And so that's all there
is to that.

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:44.950
Now let's do the second
example here.

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:46.960
We have sine theta
cosine theta.

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:48.380
So same exact idea.

00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:52.550
Here we have a product rule
as our first step.

00:02:52.550 --> 00:02:54.760
So OK, so we take the derivative
of the first times

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:56.010
the second.

00:02:59.140 --> 00:02:59.558
So the derivative, the
differential of the first, I

00:02:59.558 --> 00:02:59.590
should say.

00:02:59.590 --> 00:02:59.606
Right?

00:02:59.606 --> 00:03:01.740
So the product rule for
differentials is just the same

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:03.590
as the product rule for
derivatives except instead of

00:03:03.590 --> 00:03:05.470
taking derivatives you
take differentials.

00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:14.590
So the differential of sine
theta is cosine theta d theta.

00:03:14.590 --> 00:03:22.000
And then times the second plus
the first sine theta times the

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.170
differential of the second,
which is minus

00:03:25.170 --> 00:03:27.970
sine theta d theta.

00:03:27.970 --> 00:03:30.490
OK.

00:03:30.490 --> 00:03:33.135
And now if we like, we can,
you know, put this all

00:03:33.135 --> 00:03:36.840
together, factor out the
d theta to the end.

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:42.610
And we can rewrite this as
cosine squared theta minus

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:46.140
sine squared theta d theta.

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:47.910
And of course you could rewrite
this a bunch of other

00:03:47.910 --> 00:03:49.490
ways using your trig
identities.

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:52.000
Just like you could have started
by writing sine theta

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.250
cosine theta as 1/2 sine of
2 theta before taking the

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:56.280
differential.

00:03:56.280 --> 00:03:59.950
All right, so that's really
all there is to that.

00:03:59.950 --> 00:04:00.850
So there you go.

00:04:00.850 --> 00:04:01.940
Differentials.

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:03.610
I'll end there.